<subSubSection id="15DE5FE0FFA7EF64FF42FD07FDFBFC70" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFFA7EF64FF42FD07FBF2FC1D" blockId="15.[151,1437,617,969]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FFA7EF64FF42FD07FEE7FD74" bold="true" box="[199,338,690,716]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Comments:</emphasis>
This species is currently considered as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="9AC477E8FFA7EF64FB8BFD07FEAAFD48" authority="(De Geer, 1773)" baseAuthorityName="De Geer" baseAuthorityYear="1773" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Neoconocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculatus">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FFA7EF64FB8BFD07FADCFD74" box="[1038,1385,690,716]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Neoconocephalus tuberculatus</emphasis>
(De Geer, 1773)
</taxonomicName>
. However, when studying the collected specimens, we observed some differences between this species and 
<taxonomicName id="9AC477E8FFA7EF64FF42FD4EFEC1FCAC" baseAuthorityName="De Geer" baseAuthorityYear="1773" box="[199,372,762,788]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Neoconocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculatus">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FFA7EF64FF42FD4EFEC1FCAC" box="[199,372,762,788]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">N. tuberculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(analyzed through photos of 
<typeStatus id="827FB2C9FFA7EF64FD3AFD4FFC91FCAC" box="[703,804,762,788]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">holotype</typeStatus>
, available at OSF): (1) tibia I and II black; (2) femur III with black colour in the apical half, and with spines of different colour; (3) conical vertex, much longer than wide; (4) fastigium of the vertex black; (5) A2 vein dorsally distinct and with a colour that varies from black to light yellow; (6) rounded mirror. This is the southernmost record of the species, which was only previously recorded in the North of the country. So, this is the first record of the species for the Atlantic Forest.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFFA7EF64FF42FC1BFDFBFC70" blockId="15.[151,1437,617,969]" box="[199,590,942,969]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FFA7EF64FF42FC1BFED1FC70" bold="true" box="[199,356,942,968]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Bioacoustics:</emphasis>
